---
// Hero — photo + writeup using CSS grid-template-areas for responsive reflow.
//
// Layout behavior:
//   • <lg (phone + tablet): single column. Order is
//       heading → photo → body → cta
//     So the photo sits BETWEEN the name/intro block and the body copy,
//     rather than getting dumped on top of a long text scroll. The HTML
//     order never changes, only the grid areas reflow at the breakpoint.
//   • ≥lg (desktop): two columns. Photo LEFT, spanning all rows; heading,
//     body, and CTA stacked in the RIGHT column.
//
// TODO (Sridevi): paragraphs below are your edited version. Tune freely.
//
// Alternatives to the current subtitle ("A systems mind, now building with AI."):
//   • "A strategic operator, now building with AI."
//   • "Structurer of complex programs, now building with AI."
//   • (or drop it entirely)
//
// Paragraph 2 closing line alternatives (current: "Shipping them is how I'm
// learning what this new toolchain can and can't do."):
//   • "Each one is a way of finding out, hands-on, where this toolchain
//      holds up and where it doesn't."
//   • "They're how I'm figuring out what this toolchain is actually
//      good at."
---

<section class="px-6 md:px-10 pt-16 md:pt-24 pb-8 md:pb-12">
  <div class="mx-auto w-full max-w-6xl">
    <div class="hero-grid">

      <!-- HEADING area: kicker, name, subtitle, credentials, "open to new roles" badge -->
      <div class="hero-area-heading flex flex-col">
        <p class="font-mono text-sm text-ink-muted dark:text-neutral-400 mb-3">
          Hi, I'm Sri.
        </p>

        <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-tight">
          Sridevi<br class="hidden lg:block"/> Vijayaraghavan
        </h1>

        <p class="mt-5 text-lg md:text-xl text-ink dark:text-neutral-100 font-medium">
          A systems mind, now building with AI.
        </p>

        <p class="mt-2 font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-ink-subtle dark:text-neutral-500">
          Ex&ndash;VMware &middot; Dartmouth MBA
        </p>

        <div class="mt-5 inline-flex self-start items-center gap-2 rounded-full bg-accent-subtle dark:bg-indigo-950/40 border border-accent/20 dark:border-indigo-800/40 px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium text-accent dark:text-indigo-300">
          <span class="relative flex h-2 w-2">
            <span class="absolute inline-flex h-full w-full animate-ping rounded-full bg-accent opacity-60"></span>
            <span class="relative inline-flex h-2 w-2 rounded-full bg-accent"></span>
          </span>
          Open to new roles
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- PHOTO area: one element, reflows across breakpoints via grid-area -->
      <div class="hero-area-photo">
        <div class="photo-frame relative overflow-hidden rounded-md border border-neutral-200 dark:border-neutral-800 bg-neutral-100 dark:bg-neutral-900">
          <img
            src="/me.jpeg"
            alt="Sridevi Vijayaraghavan"
            class="w-full h-full object-cover"
            loading="eager"
          />
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- BODY: the three paragraphs -->
      <div class="hero-area-body max-w-2xl space-y-4 text-[1.05rem] leading-relaxed text-ink-muted dark:text-neutral-300">
        <p>
          I spent ~6 years at VMware as a Technical Program Manager,
          orchestrating complex release programs across large engineering
          orgs. I went to Tuck for an MBA &mdash; business fundamentals,
          with an emphasis on strategy, entrepreneurship, and venture.
          Somewhere in the middle of all that, generative AI reset what
          one person could build alone.
        </p>
        <p>
          So I've been building: a gamified system-design curriculum with a
          real pedagogy, a museum-style web experience about cinema and
          technology, a pricing intelligence dashboard that pulls structure
          out of scraped SaaS pages with an LLM. Shipping them is how I'm
          learning what this new toolchain can and can't do.
        </p>
        <p>
          I'm open to new roles &mdash; where I can structure processes,
          leverage AI, stand up functions, and above all, keep learning.
          <a
            href="mailto:vijayaraghavansridevi@gmail.com"
            class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover dark:text-indigo-400 dark:hover:text-indigo-300 transition underline decoration-accent/40 underline-offset-2"
          >Say hi</a>
          if that sounds like what you're hiring for.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- CTA buttons -->
      <div class="hero-area-cta flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a
          href="#projects"
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-md bg-accent px-5 py-2.5 text-sm font-medium text-white hover:bg-accent-hover transition"
        >
          See projects
          <span aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span>
        </a>
        <a
          href="#contact"
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-md border border-neutral-200 dark:border-neutral-800 px-5 py-2.5 text-sm font-medium text-ink dark:text-neutral-100 hover:border-neutral-300 dark:hover:border-neutral-700 transition"
        >
          Get in touch
        </a>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<style>
  /* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
     Base (mobile + tablet, <lg): single column.
     HTML order stays the same; grid-template-areas places the photo
     between heading and body.
     ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
  .hero-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    grid-template-areas:
      "heading"
      "photo"
      "body"
      "cta";
  }

  .hero-area-heading { grid-area: heading; }
  .hero-area-photo   { grid-area: photo;   }
  .hero-area-body    { grid-area: body;    }
  .hero-area-cta     { grid-area: cta;     }

  /* Vertical rhythm between the four areas in single-column mode */
  .hero-area-photo { margin-top: 1.75rem; }
  .hero-area-body  { margin-top: 1.5rem;  }
  .hero-area-cta   { margin-top: 2.25rem; }

  /* Photo frame — single-column (phone + tablet):
     Use a short, landscape-ish aspect so the photo doesn't dominate the
     viewport and push body copy below the fold. object-position crops
     from the bottom, keeping the face in frame — swap aspect + crop
     position at narrower widths instead of keeping portrait everywhere. */
  .photo-frame {
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 640px;
    aspect-ratio: 3 / 2;      /* landscape-ish — wide, not tall */
    margin-left: auto;
    margin-right: auto;
  }
  .photo-frame img {
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center 35%;  /* bias upward → keep face, drop torso */
  }

  /* Slightly taller photo on small tablets for a bit more presence */
  @media (min-width: 640px) {
    .photo-frame {
      aspect-ratio: 16 / 10;
      max-width: 720px;
      max-height: 460px;
    }
  }

  /* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
     Desktop (≥lg, 1024px+): two columns.
     Photo spans all three rows on the LEFT; text column stacks on the RIGHT.
     ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
  @media (min-width: 1024px) {
    .hero-grid {
      grid-template-columns: auto 1fr;
      column-gap: 3.5rem;
      grid-template-areas:
        "photo heading"
        "photo body"
        "photo cta";
    }

    /* Reset the single-column spacing that we added above. */
    .hero-area-photo { margin-top: 3.5rem; align-self: start; }
    .hero-area-body  { margin-top: 2rem;   }
    .hero-area-cta   { margin-top: 2.5rem; }

    /* Photo becomes fixed-size portrait at desktop — full frame */
    .photo-frame {
      width: 410px;
      max-width: none;
      max-height: none;
      height: 570px;
      aspect-ratio: auto;
      margin-left: 0;
      margin-right: 0;
    }
    .photo-frame img {
      object-position: center center;  /* restore full portrait framing */
    }
  }

  /* Slightly larger photo at xl+ for big monitors (optional polish) */
  @media (min-width: 1280px) {
    .photo-frame {
      width: 440px;
      height: 610px;
    }
  }
</style>
